<subSubSection id="0DFA65634A7CE00DFF0CF8F0FEF2F81C" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" type="materials_examined">
<paragraph id="455F36E84A7CE00DFF0CF8F0FEF2F81C" blockId="16.[151,1436,1899,2034]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">
<emphasis id="7794EAFA4A7CE00DFF0CF8F0FEA4F868" bold="true" box="[151,260,1900,1926]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Remarks</emphasis>
. Specimens of this species were not studied. 
<bibRefCitation id="21714B194A7CE00DFC8AF8F7FC1CF868" author="Nielson, M. W." box="[785,956,1899,1926]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" pagination="445 - 475" refId="ref38693" refString="Nielson, M. W. (1991) New Oriental leafhoppers in the tribe Coelidiini with a revised key to the species (Homoptera: Cicadellidae: Coelidiinae). Entomologica Scandinavica, 21, 445 - 475. https: // doi. org / 10.1163 / 187631290 X 00355" type="journal article" year="1991">Nielson (1991)</bibRefCitation>
adequeately described and illustrated this speices based on a male collected from 
<collectingRegion id="8724F80A4A7CE00DFDC2F80CFD05F844" box="[601,677,1936,1962]" country="India" name="Assam" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Assam</collectingRegion>
(
<collectingCountry id="3DF776784A7CE00DFD2EF813FD54F844" box="[693,756,1935,1962]" name="India" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">India</collectingCountry>
). Among the species of the genus, this species can be easily recognized by the long, apically hooked pygofer process (
<figureCitation id="DDDB2A6D4A7CE00DFC86F82FFC27F820" box="[797,903,1971,1998]" captionStart="FIGURES 24" captionStartId="59.[151,264,1817,1842]" captionTargetBox="[213,1375,223,1763]" captionTargetId="figure@59.[151,1436,181,1797]" captionTargetPageId="59" captionText="FIGURES 24 A–V. Species of Creberulidia Nielson and Hiatusorus Nielson, male genitalia. A–D. Creberulidia excelsa (Distant); E–H. C. pica (Nielson); I–L. C. quadrispinata (Nielson); M–Q. Hiatusorus concavus (Nielson); R–V. H. hardyi (Nielson). Modified and reproduced from Nielson 1982 (Figs. A–H, M–Q), Nielson 1991 (Figs. I–L) and Nielson 2015 (Figs. R–V)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3366592/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Fig. 24 R</figureCitation>
) and by the curved apex of the apophysis of the style (
<figureCitation id="DDDB2A6D4A7CE00DFF40F84BFEE5F81C" box="[219,325,2007,2034]" captionStart="FIGURES 24" captionStartId="59.[151,264,1817,1842]" captionTargetBox="[213,1375,223,1763]" captionTargetId="figure@59.[151,1436,181,1797]" captionTargetPageId="59" captionText="FIGURES 24 A–V. Species of Creberulidia Nielson and Hiatusorus Nielson, male genitalia. A–D. Creberulidia excelsa (Distant); E–H. C. pica (Nielson); I–L. C. quadrispinata (Nielson); M–Q. Hiatusorus concavus (Nielson); R–V. H. hardyi (Nielson). Modified and reproduced from Nielson 1982 (Figs. A–H, M–Q), Nielson 1991 (Figs. I–L) and Nielson 2015 (Figs. R–V)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3366592/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Fig. 24 S</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
